if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['oph_p2_eyelid']=[
  {q:"An elderly patient presents with a pearly nodular lesion with rolled edges and telangiectatic vessels on the lower eyelid. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Chalazion","Keratoacanthoma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the most common malignant eyelid tumor and classically appears as a pearly nodular lesion with rolled margins and surface telangiectasia.<br><br>The lower eyelid and medial canthus are the most commonly affected sites due to chronic ultraviolet exposure.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) frequently masquerades as chalazion or blepharitis rather than presenting with pearly rolled edges. Squamous cell carcinoma (C) is generally more ulcerative and keratinizing. ([[Review of<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent chalazion in an elderly patient should always raise suspicion for:",o:["Papilloma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Hemangioma","Neurofibroma"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a highly malignant eyelid tumor notorious for masquerading as recurrent chalazion or chronic unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis significantly increases risk of orbital invasion and metastasis. Basal cell carcinoma as the commonest lid malignancy with its pearly rolled margin is a classic recognition theme.<br><br>Papilloma (A) is benign and usually pedunculated. Basal cell carcinoma (C) typically presents with ulcerative pearly nodules rather than recurrent chalazion-like swelling.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which malignant eyelid tumor most commonly affects the lower eyelid?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Melanoma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma most commonly involves the lower eyelid because of chronic sun exposure affecting the inferior periocular region.<br><br>It accounts for the majority of malignant eyelid tumors in Western populations.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (B) more commonly involves the upper eyelid due to greater density of meibomian glands. Capillary hemangioma (E) is a benign vascular tumor of infancy. ([[Review of<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid malignancy demonstrates pagetoid spread histologically?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Keratoacanthoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Nevus"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma characteristically demonstrates pagetoid intraepithelial spread involving conjunctiva and eyelid epithelium.<br><br>This feature contributes to delayed diagnosis and high recurrence rates.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) is locally invasive but does not classically show pagetoid spread. Keratoacanthoma (C) is rapidly growing but comparatively less aggressive. ([[SRS<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless yellowish upper eyelid nodule with madarosis in an elderly woman is most suggestive of:",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Chalazion","Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma often presents as a painless yellowish upper eyelid mass associated with eyelash loss due to follicular infiltration.<br><br>Upper eyelid involvement is common because of abundant meibomian glands.<br><br>Chalazion (B) usually lacks madarosis and malignant infiltration. Hordeolum (E) is painful and inflammatory rather than indolent malignant disease. ([[SRS<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor is locally invasive but rarely metastasizes?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Merkel cell carcinoma"],a:2,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is locally destructive and may invade orbit if neglected, but distant metastasis is extremely rare.<br><br>It is therefore considered a malignant yet relatively low-metastatic eyelid tumor.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) and melanoma (D) possess greater metastatic potential and mortality risk than basal cell carcinoma. ([[Review of<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical sign strongly suggests sebaceous gland carcinoma over chalazion?",o:["Painful swelling","Watering only","Bilateral disease","Madarosis","Photophobia"],a:3,e:"Loss of eyelashes or madarosis is an important warning sign suggesting malignant eyelid infiltration, especially sebaceous gland carcinoma.<br><br>Painful swelling (A) is more characteristic of acute hordeolum. Bilateral disease (C) is uncommon in sebaceous gland carcinoma. ([[SRS<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which malignant eyelid tumor is considered the third most common after basal and squamous cell carcinoma?",o:["Melanoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Neurofibroma","Hemangioma","Papilloma"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is classically described as the third most common malignant eyelid tumor after basal and squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>It is particularly important in Asian populations and has aggressive biological behavior.<br><br>Melanoma (A) is less common in eyelid malignancies. Papilloma (E) is a benign epithelial lesion rather than malignant neoplasm.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor is most strongly associated with chronic ultraviolet exposure?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Chalazion","Dermoid cyst","Nevus"],a:0,e:"Chronic ultraviolet radiation is the major etiological factor for basal cell carcinoma involving periocular skin and eyelids.<br><br>Fair-skinned elderly individuals are at increased risk.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (B) is linked more with meibomian gland origin and masquerade syndromes than direct UV-related pathogenesis. ([[Review of<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly enlarging ulcerative eyelid lesion with keratinization is most suggestive of:",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Nevus","Papilloma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Hemangioma"],a:3,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma commonly presents as an ulcerative hyperkeratotic eyelid lesion with irregular borders and invasive behavior.<br><br>Regional lymphatic spread is more common than with basal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) often masquerades as chalazion rather than hyperkeratotic ulcerative lesions. Papilloma (C) is benign and noninvasive.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid malignancy most commonly arises from meibomian glands?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Squamous papilloma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Nevus"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma originates from meibomian glands, glands of Zeis, or sebaceous glands of the caruncle.<br><br>Upper eyelid involvement predominates because of higher meibomian gland density.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) arises from basal epidermal cells rather than sebaceous structures. Melanoma (B) originates from melanocytes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion is commonly pedunculated and associated with HPV infection?",o:["Papilloma","Sebaceous carcinoma","Chalazion","Keratoacanthoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],a:0,e:"Squamous papilloma is a benign epithelial tumor frequently presenting as pedunculated eyelid growth associated with human papillomavirus infection.<br><br>These lesions are usually slow-growing and noninvasive.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (E) demonstrates destructive malignant growth rather than benign papillary projections. Chalazion (C) is inflammatory lipogranuloma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor has the highest risk of local recurrence and metastasis among common lid malignancies?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Nevus","Papilloma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Xanthelasma"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is highly aggressive and carries substantial risk of recurrence, pagetoid spread, lymphatic dissemination, and metastasis.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis contributes significantly to mortality.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) is locally invasive but metastasizes rarely. Xanthelasma (E) is a benign lipid deposition disorder. ([[SAS<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which warning feature in a presumed chalazion should prompt biopsy?",o:["Pain","Recurrent lesion in same location","Watering only","Photophobia","Bilateral itching"],a:1,e:"A recurrent chalazion at the same site, especially in elderly patients, should always undergo biopsy to exclude sebaceous gland carcinoma.<br><br>This is one of the most.<br><br>Pain (A) more commonly indicates inflammatory hordeolum. Bilateral itching (E) suggests allergic disease rather than malignancy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid malignancy most frequently invades the medial canthus?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Papilloma","Nevus","Hemangioma","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma commonly affects the medial canthus and lower eyelid because of cumulative ultraviolet exposure.<br><br>Medial canthal lesions may spread deeply into orbit and lacrimal drainage structures.<br><br>Papilloma (B) and hemangioma (D) are benign lesions without destructive medial canthal invasion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A firm painless eyelid lesion associated with chronic unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis is most suggestive of:",o:["Hordeolum","Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Xanthelasma"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma frequently masquerades as chronic unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis because of diffuse pagetoid epithelial spread.<br><br>Persistent unilateral disease in elderly individuals should raise suspicion for malignancy.<br><br>Hordeolum (A) is painful and acute. Xanthelasma (E) presents as yellow lipid plaques rather than infiltrative inflammatory-appearing masses.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid lesion is considered a lipogranulomatous inflammation rather than true neoplasm?",o:["Chalazion","Sebaceous carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Papilloma","Melanoma"],a:0,e:"Chalazion represents chronic lipogranulomatous inflammation caused by meibomian gland blockage rather than a true neoplastic lesion.<br><br>It is usually painless and slowly enlarging.<br><br>Sebaceous carcinoma (B) may clinically mimic chalazion but demonstrates malignant invasive cellular proliferation histologically. Melanoma (E) arises from melanocytes.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor most commonly presents as a painless ulcer with rolled translucent borders?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Nevus"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma classically appears as a painless ulcerative lesion with pearly translucent rolled borders and telangiectatic vessels.<br><br>This morphology is highly characteristic in examination recalls.<br><br>Squamous cell carcinoma (B) demonstrates more keratinization and crusting. Sebaceous gland carcinoma (C) often resembles chalazion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor commonly demonstrates yellow coloration because of lipid-rich cells?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Papilloma","Basal cell carcinoma","Dermoid cyst","Hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma may appear yellowish clinically because tumor cells contain lipid-rich sebaceous material.<br><br>The lesion is usually firm, painless, and commonly located in upper eyelid.<br><br>Hemangioma (E) is vascular and reddish rather than yellow. Basal cell carcinoma (C) classically appears pearly translucent. ([[Gavin<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding sebaceous gland carcinoma is most accurate?",o:["It is usually painful","It commonly affects children","It never metastasizes","It often mimics benign inflammatory disease","It predominantly affects lower eyelid"],a:3,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is well known as a \"masquerade tumor\" because it frequently mimics chalazion, blepharitis, or chronic conjunctivitis.<br><br>This deceptive presentation causes delayed diagnosis and worsened prognosis.<br><br>The tumor commonly affects elderly individuals and has metastatic potential. Upper eyelid involvement is more frequent because of greater meibomian gland density.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"An elderly patient presents with inward turning of the lower eyelid causing lashes to rub against the cornea. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Ectropion","Entropion","Ptosis","Dermatochalasis","Lagophthalmos"],a:1,e:"Entropion refers to inward turning of the eyelid margin, most commonly involving the lower eyelid in elderly individuals.<br><br>Trichiasis and corneal irritation commonly occur because eyelashes rub against the ocular surface. Involutional entropion with its mechanism in the elderly is a recurring lid-malposition question.<br><br>Ectropion (A) involves outward turning of the eyelid. Lagophthalmos (E) is inability to close eyelids completely rather than inversion of lid margin.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of ectropion is most commonly associated with aging and horizontal lid laxity?",o:["Cicatricial ectropion","Paralytic ectropion","Mechanical ectropion","Involutional ectropion","Congenital ectropion"],a:3,e:"Involutional ectropion is the commonest type and results from age-related horizontal lid laxity and weakening of canthal tendons.<br><br>The lower eyelid gradually everts away from the globe causing epiphora and conjunctival exposure.<br><br>Cicatricial ectropion (A) results from skin scarring and contracture rather than age-related laxity. Paralytic ectropion (B) follows facial nerve palsy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with facial nerve palsy develops outward turning of the lower eyelid. Which type of ectropion is present?",o:["Congenital ectropion","Mechanical ectropion","Paralytic ectropion","Cicatricial ectropion","Spastic ectropion"],a:2,e:"Paralytic ectropion occurs because facial nerve palsy weakens orbicularis oculi muscle, leading to lower eyelid eversion and poor lid apposition.<br><br>Exposure keratopathy and epiphora are common complications. Ectropion with exposure keratopathy risk is a recurring lid-malposition correlate.<br><br>Mechanical ectropion (B) results from tumors or heavy lesions pulling the eyelid outward. Cicatricial ectropion (D) occurs due to scarring.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which complication is most commonly associated with entropion?",o:["Cataract","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal ulceration","Macular edema"],a:3,e:"Entropion causes lashes and skin to abrade the corneal surface repeatedly, predisposing to epithelial defects and corneal ulceration.<br><br>Persistent irritation also leads to watering, redness, and photophobia.<br><br>Cataract (A) affects the crystalline lens and is unrelated to lid malposition. Retinal detachment (B) involves neurosensory retinal separation rather than ocular surface trauma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of entropion is commonly caused by conjunctival scarring?",o:["Spastic entropion","Senile entropion","Congenital entropion","Cicatricial entropion","Mechanical entropion"],a:3,e:"Cicatricial entropion develops when conjunctival scarring contracts the posterior lamella, rotating the eyelid inward toward the globe.<br><br>Trachoma and ocular cicatricial pemphigoid are important causes.<br><br>Senile entropion (B) results from age-related lid laxity rather than conjunctival fibrosis. Spastic entropion (A) occurs due to orbicularis muscle spasm.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most characteristic of ectropion?",o:["Foreign body sensation from lashes","Epiphora","Colored halos","Diplopia","Night blindness"],a:1,e:"Ectropion causes outward displacement of the punctum, preventing normal tear drainage and resulting in watering or epiphora.<br><br>Exposure of conjunctiva also contributes to irritation and chronic conjunctivitis.<br><br>Foreign body sensation from lash-cornea touch (A) is more characteristic of entropion. Colored halos (C) are associated with corneal edema in glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid structure becomes lax in involutional entropion?",o:["Lens capsule","Corneal stroma","Retina","Lower lid retractors","Iris sphincter"],a:3,e:"Involutional entropion develops because of lower lid retractor weakness, horizontal lid laxity, and overriding orbicularis muscle.<br><br>These age-related changes rotate the eyelid margin inward.<br><br>Corneal stroma (B) and retina (C) are unrelated intraocular structures unaffected directly by eyelid laxity. Iris sphincter (E) controls pupillary constriction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of ectropion commonly occurs after burns or trauma?",o:["Paralytic ectropion","Mechanical ectropion","Cicatricial ectropion","Congenital ectropion","Senile ectropion"],a:2,e:"Cicatricial ectropion occurs when scarring and contracture of eyelid skin pull the lid margin away from the globe.<br><br>Burns, trauma, and chronic dermatitis are important causes.<br><br>Senile ectropion (E) is associated with aging changes and horizontal lid laxity. Paralytic ectropion (A) results from facial nerve palsy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which disease is a classic cause of cicatricial entropion in developing countries?",o:["Glaucoma","Cataract","Keratoconus","Trachoma","Retinal detachment"],a:3,e:"Trachoma causes chronic conjunctival inflammation and fibrosis leading to cicatricial entropion and trichiasis.<br><br>Corneal scarring from repeated lash trauma is an important cause of preventable blindness.<br><br>Cataract (B) affects the lens and does not produce conjunctival scarring. Keratoconus (C) is a corneal ectatic disorder unrelated to lid inversion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of entropion is caused by orbicularis oculi spasm?",o:["Cicatricial entropion","Mechanical entropion","Congenital entropion","Spastic entropion","Senile entropion"],a:3,e:"Spastic entropion occurs when excessive contraction of orbicularis oculi muscle rotates the eyelid margin inward.<br><br>It is often triggered by ocular irritation or inflammation.<br><br>Cicatricial entropion (A) results from conjunctival fibrosis. Senile entropion (E) develops because of age-related lid laxity and retractor weakness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which sign is commonly seen in entropion?",o:["Punctal eversion","Exophthalmos","Lagophthalmos","Trichiasis","Leukocoria"],a:3,e:"Entropion rotates eyelashes inward toward the globe, producing secondary trichiasis and corneal irritation.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of watering, redness, and foreign body sensation.<br><br>Punctal eversion (A) is more characteristic of ectropion. Leukocoria (E) indicates white pupillary reflex rather than eyelid malposition.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid condition most commonly causes exposure keratopathy?",o:["Entropion","Ectropion","Chalazion","Xanthelasma","Hordeolum"],a:1,e:"Ectropion prevents proper lid-globe apposition, exposing conjunctiva and cornea to drying and environmental irritation.<br><br>Exposure keratopathy may develop in severe untreated cases.<br><br>Entropion (A) mainly causes lash-induced corneal trauma rather than exposure-related dryness. Chalazion (C) is a localized lipogranulomatous inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which surgical procedure is commonly performed for involutional ectropion?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Penetrating keratoplasty","Dacryocystectomy","Lateral tarsal strip procedure","Scleral buckle"],a:3,e:"Lateral tarsal strip procedure corrects horizontal lid laxity and restores proper eyelid tension in involutional ectropion.<br><br>It also improves punctal positioning and tear drainage.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (A) is a glaucoma surgery. Penetrating keratoplasty (B) is corneal transplantation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom strongly suggests entropion rather than ectropion?",o:["Watering due to punctal eversion","Lid eversion","Chronic conjunctival exposure","Foreign body sensation from lash touch","Facial nerve palsy"],a:3,e:"Entropion causes eyelashes to rub against the cornea and conjunctiva, producing foreign body sensation and irritation.<br><br>Corneal epithelial damage may occur with prolonged disease.<br><br>Punctal eversion (A) and chronic conjunctival exposure (C) are more typical of ectropion. Facial nerve palsy (E) commonly produces paralytic ectropion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of ectropion is caused by heavy tumors pulling the eyelid downward?",o:["Cicatricial ectropion","Mechanical ectropion","Paralytic ectropion","Senile ectropion","Congenital ectropion"],a:1,e:"Mechanical ectropion occurs when tumors, edema, or other heavy lesions exert downward traction on the eyelid margin.<br><br>Correction depends on treatment of the underlying cause.<br><br>Paralytic ectropion (C) results from orbicularis muscle weakness due to facial nerve palsy. Senile ectropion (D) develops because of lid laxity.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which test is useful for assessing horizontal lid laxity in ectropion?",o:["Seidel test","Ishihara test","Cover test","Lid distraction test","Schirmer test"],a:3,e:"Lid distraction test assesses horizontal eyelid laxity by measuring how far the lower eyelid can be pulled away from the globe.<br><br>Excessive displacement supports involutional ectropion.<br><br>Schirmer test (E) measures tear production. Ishihara test (B) evaluates color vision deficiency.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of entropion occurs because of aging changes?",o:["Cicatricial entropion","Spastic entropion","Senile entropion","Congenital entropion","Mechanical entropion"],a:2,e:"Senile or involutional entropion occurs because of age-related lid laxity, lower lid retractor disinsertion, and orbicularis muscle override.<br><br>The lower eyelid is affected most commonly.<br><br>Congenital entropion (D) presents at birth. Cicatricial entropion (A) results from conjunctival scarring.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which complication is most feared in untreated entropion?",o:["Cataract formation","Retinal tear","Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal scarring","Optic atrophy"],a:3,e:"Persistent lash-cornea friction in untreated entropion may lead to recurrent epithelial injury, ulceration, and permanent corneal scarring.<br><br>Visual impairment may result if the visual axis becomes involved.<br><br>Retinal tear (B) and vitreous hemorrhage (C) are posterior segment disorders unrelated to lid inversion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid abnormality is associated with punctal eversion?",o:["Entropion","Blepharospasm","Trichiasis","Ectropion","Ptosis"],a:3,e:"Ectropion causes outward turning of the eyelid margin including the lacrimal punctum, impairing tear drainage.<br><br>Epiphora is therefore a common presenting symptom.<br><br>Entropion (A) rotates the eyelid inward rather than outward. Ptosis (E) refers to drooping of the upper eyelid.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding involutional ectropion is most accurate?",o:["It usually affects children","It is caused by conjunctival scarring","It commonly results from age-related lid laxity","It produces inward turning of lashes","It is always associated with trauma"],a:2,e:"Involutional ectropion develops because of age-related horizontal lid laxity and weakening of canthal tendon support.<br><br>The lower eyelid gradually everts away from the globe.<br><br>Conjunctival scarring (B) causes cicatricial ectropion rather than involutional disease. Inward turning of lashes (D) occurs in entropion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with complete ptosis, \"down and out\" eye position, and dilated pupil most likely has paralysis of which cranial nerve?",o:["Optic nerve","Trochlear nerve","Oculomotor nerve","Abducens nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"Third cranial nerve palsy classically produces complete ptosis because levator palpebrae superioris loses innervation.<br><br>Associated ophthalmoplegia and pupillary dilation are important accompanying findings.<br><br>Trochlear nerve palsy (B) causes vertical diplopia without severe ptosis. Facial nerve palsy (E) affects eyelid closure rather than elevation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which muscle is primarily responsible for elevation of the upper eyelid?",o:["Orbicularis oculi","Superior rectus","Muller muscle","Levator palpebrae superioris","Frontalis"],a:3,e:"Levator palpebrae superioris is the principal elevator of the upper eyelid and receives innervation from the oculomotor nerve.<br><br>Its dysfunction is the major cause of true ptosis.<br><br>Muller muscle (C) contributes minor sympathetic eyelid elevation. Orbicularis oculi (A) closes the eyelids rather than elevating them.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Mild ptosis associated with miosis and anhidrosis is characteristic of:",o:["Third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Horner syndrome","Marcus Gunn jaw-winking","Chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia"],a:2,e:"Horner syndrome results from sympathetic pathway interruption and classically presents with mild ptosis, miosis, and facial anhidrosis.<br><br>Ptosis occurs because Muller muscle loses sympathetic innervation.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) usually produces severe ptosis with ophthalmoplegia and pupillary dilation rather than miosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most useful in suspected myasthenic ptosis?",o:["Schirmer test","Keratometry","Gonioscopy","Ice pack test","Fluorescein angiography"],a:3,e:"Ice pack test temporarily improves ptosis in myasthenia gravis because cooling enhances neuromuscular transmission.<br><br>The test is.<br><br>Fluorescein angiography (E) evaluates retinal vasculature. Gonioscopy (C) examines anterior chamber angle rather than neuromuscular junction disorders.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital ptosis is at greatest risk of developing:",o:["Cataract","Retinal detachment","Glaucoma","Optic neuritis","Amblyopia"],a:4,e:"Congenital ptosis may obstruct the visual axis during visual development, resulting in deprivation amblyopia.<br><br>Prompt evaluation and surgical correction are important when the pupil is covered.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) and optic neuritis (D) are unrelated to eyelid drooping. Glaucoma (C) is not a direct consequence of congenital ptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is characterized by fluctuating ptosis worsening toward evening?",o:["Horner syndrome","Third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Congenital ptosis","Blepharophimosis syndrome"],a:2,e:"Myasthenia gravis commonly produces fatigable ptosis that worsens with prolonged activity and improves with rest.<br><br>Diplopia due to variable extraocular muscle weakness is also common.<br><br>Congenital ptosis (D) remains relatively constant rather than fluctuating. Horner syndrome (A) produces mild stable ptosis with miosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which muscle loses sympathetic innervation in Horner syndrome?",o:["Levator palpebrae superioris","Superior rectus","Inferior oblique","Orbicularis oculi","Muller muscle"],a:4,e:"Muller muscle is sympathetically innervated and contributes approximately 2 mm of upper eyelid elevation.<br><br>Its denervation causes mild ptosis in Horner syndrome.<br><br>Levator palpebrae superioris (A) is supplied by the oculomotor nerve rather than sympathetic fibers. Orbicularis oculi (D) closes the eyelids.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Severe unilateral ptosis with ophthalmoplegia and mydriasis should raise suspicion for:",o:["Horner syndrome","Myasthenia gravis","Third nerve palsy","Blepharitis","Congenital ptosis"],a:2,e:"Third nerve palsy classically causes severe ptosis, \"down and out\" eye deviation, and pupillary dilation when parasympathetic fibers are involved.<br><br>Posterior communicating artery aneurysm must be excluded urgently.<br><br>Horner syndrome (A) produces mild ptosis with miosis rather than mydriasis. Myasthenia gravis (B) usually spares the pupil.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which clinical feature favors myasthenic ptosis over congenital ptosis?",o:["Poor levator function","Lid lag on downgaze","Chin elevation posture","Absent lid crease","Variability of ptosis"],a:4,e:"Myasthenic ptosis fluctuates in severity throughout the day because of fatigable neuromuscular transmission failure.<br><br>Variability is an important distinguishing feature in examination recalls.<br><br>Absent lid crease (D) and poor levator function (A) are more typical of congenital ptosis. Chin elevation posture (C) occurs in severe congenital cases.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which sign is commonly associated with congenital ptosis?",o:["Elevated lid crease","Good levator function","Poor lid crease formation","Miosis","Facial anhidrosis"],a:2,e:"Congenital ptosis commonly demonstrates poor or absent upper lid crease because levator muscle development is defective.<br><br>Levator function is frequently reduced.<br><br>Miosis (D) and anhidrosis (E) suggest Horner syndrome rather than congenital myogenic ptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ptosis improves after edrophonium administration. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Horner syndrome","Third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Congenital ptosis","Marcus Gunn phenomenon"],a:2,e:"Edrophonium temporarily improves neuromuscular transmission in myasthenia gravis, leading to transient improvement in ptosis and ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>This pharmacologic response is classically tested in neuro-ophthalmology recalls.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (B) results from nerve dysfunction and does not improve with anticholinesterase agents. Congenital ptosis (D) is structural.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which surgical procedure is preferred in severe congenital ptosis with poor levator function?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Frontalis sling surgery","Dacryocystorhinostomy","Lateral tarsal strip","Blepharoplasty"],a:1,e:"Frontalis sling surgery suspends the eyelid from frontalis muscle, allowing brow elevation to assist eyelid opening in severe congenital ptosis.<br><br>It is indicated when levator function is poor.<br><br>Blepharoplasty (E) removes excess skin rather than correcting severe ptosis. Lateral tarsal strip (D) treats ectropion and entropion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which syndrome combines ptosis with synkinetic eyelid elevation during jaw movement?",o:["Horner syndrome","Duane syndrome","Adie syndrome","Brown syndrome","Marcus Gunn jaw-winking syndrome"],a:4,e:"Marcus Gunn jaw-winking syndrome is a congenital synkinetic phenomenon in which eyelid elevation occurs during chewing or jaw movement.<br><br>It results from aberrant neural connections between trigeminal and oculomotor pathways.<br><br>Horner syndrome (A) causes mild ptosis and miosis without jaw-winking movements. Brown syndrome (D) affects superior oblique tendon function.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of ptosis is caused by dehiscence of levator aponeurosis in elderly individuals?",o:["Neurogenic ptosis","Mechanical ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Myogenic ptosis","Congenital ptosis"],a:2,e:"Aponeurotic ptosis results from stretching or dehiscence of the levator aponeurosis, particularly in elderly individuals.<br><br>High eyelid crease and good levator function are characteristic findings.<br><br>Myogenic ptosis (D) results from intrinsic muscle dysfunction. Mechanical ptosis (B) occurs due to heavy masses pulling the eyelid downward.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition produces mild ptosis with normal ocular movements and constricted pupil?",o:["Third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Congenital fibrosis syndrome","Orbital cellulitis","Horner syndrome"],a:4,e:"Horner syndrome classically presents with mild ptosis, miosis, and preserved ocular motility because sympathetic innervation is interrupted.<br><br>Anhidrosis may also occur depending on lesion location.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) causes ophthalmoplegia and mydriasis rather than constricted pupil. Myasthenia gravis (B) spares pupillary function.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which bedside finding strongly supports myasthenia gravis in a ptosis patient?",o:["Cherry-red spot","Fatigability on sustained upgaze","Relative afferent pupillary defect","Marcus Gunn pupil","Corneal opacity"],a:1,e:"Sustained upgaze worsens ptosis in myasthenia gravis because repetitive muscle use exhausts neuromuscular transmission.<br><br>This fatigability is highly characteristic clinically. Localising the cause of ptosis from the associated signs is a recurring neuro-ophthalmic exam theme.<br><br>Relative afferent pupillary defect (C) indicates optic nerve dysfunction. Cherry-red spot (A) occurs in retinal artery occlusion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ptosis type is caused by heavy eyelid tumors mechanically pulling the lid downward?",o:["Mechanical ptosis","Neurogenic ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Congenital ptosis","Myogenic ptosis"],a:0,e:"Mechanical ptosis develops when tumors, edema, or scarring increase eyelid weight and physically pull the lid downward.<br><br>Correction depends on treating the underlying lesion.<br><br>Neurogenic ptosis (B) results from nerve dysfunction such as third nerve palsy or Horner syndrome.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which finding is most characteristic of congenital ptosis?",o:["Sudden onset","Diurnal variation","Lid lag in downgaze","Severe pain","Dilated pupil"],a:2,e:"Congenital ptosis commonly demonstrates lid lag on downgaze because the dystrophic levator muscle fails to relax normally.<br><br>Poor lid crease and reduced levator function are additional findings.<br><br>Diurnal variation (B) suggests myasthenia gravis rather than congenital myogenic ptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition should be urgently excluded in painful third nerve palsy with ptosis?",o:["Cataract","Keratoconus","Retinitis pigmentosa","Posterior communicating artery aneurysm","Macular degeneration"],a:3,e:"Painful third nerve palsy with ptosis and pupillary involvement strongly suggests compressive aneurysm, especially involving the posterior communicating artery.<br><br>Urgent neuroimaging is mandatory because rupture may be life-threatening.<br><br>Keratoconus (B) and cataract (A) do not produce cranial nerve palsies. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) primarily affects photoreceptors.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding myasthenic ptosis is most accurate?",o:["Pupillary reactions are usually abnormal","Ptosis is classically nonfluctuating","It is associated with miosis","Levator muscle is fibrosed congenitally","Symptoms worsen with fatigue"],a:4,e:"Myasthenic ptosis characteristically worsens with fatigue and improves with rest because of defective neuromuscular transmission at the motor endplate.<br><br>Diplopia and variable ocular muscle weakness are common associated findings.<br><br>Pupillary reactions are usually normal, helping distinguish myasthenia gravis from third nerve palsy or Horner syndrome.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A soft yellowish plaque near the medial canthus of both upper eyelids is most likely:",o:["Chalazion","Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Sebaceous carcinoma"],a:3,e:"Xanthelasma presents as soft yellow lipid-rich plaques near the medial canthus, commonly involving upper eyelids bilaterally.<br><br>It may be associated with hyperlipidemia, although many patients have normal lipid profiles.<br><br>Chalazion (A) is a localized meibomian gland lipogranuloma. Sebaceous carcinoma (E) is malignant and usually presents as a firm infiltrative lesion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion is caused by chronic lipogranulomatous inflammation of meibomian gland?",o:["Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Chalazion","Nevus","Hemangioma"],a:2,e:"Chalazion results from blockage of a meibomian gland with subsequent chronic lipogranulomatous inflammatory reaction.<br><br>It presents as a painless firm eyelid swelling.<br><br>Papilloma (A) is an epithelial benign tumor. Hemangioma (E) is a vascular lesion commonly seen in childhood.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A pedunculated benign epithelial lesion associated with HPV infection is called:",o:["Sebaceous cyst","Neurofibroma","Dermoid cyst","Chalazion","Papilloma"],a:4,e:"Squamous papilloma is a benign epithelial proliferation often associated with human papillomavirus infection.<br><br>It typically presents as a pedunculated or sessile eyelid mass.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (C) is congenital and subcutaneous. Neurofibroma (B) arises from peripheral nerve sheath tissue rather than epithelium.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion commonly presents at the superotemporal orbital rim in children?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Chalazion","Xanthelasma","Papilloma","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Dermoid cyst is a congenital choristoma commonly located near the frontozygomatic suture at the superotemporal orbital rim.<br><br>It presents as a painless slowly enlarging mass in childhood. A recurrent or atypical chalazion warranting biopsy to exclude sebaceous carcinoma is a classic caution.<br><br>Hordeolum (E) is painful and inflammatory. Chalazion (B) arises from meibomian glands rather than orbital sutures.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion is most strongly associated with hyperlipidemia?",o:["Chalazion","Papilloma","Hemangioma","Nevus","Xanthelasma"],a:4,e:"Xanthelasma consists of lipid-laden foam cells deposited in the dermis and may be associated with elevated serum cholesterol or triglycerides.<br><br>The lesions are cosmetically significant but benign.<br><br>Nevus (D) is a melanocytic lesion unrelated to lipid metabolism. Hemangioma (C) is vascular in origin.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A painful tender swelling at the eyelid margin involving eyelash follicle is most likely:",o:["Chalazion","Hordeolum externum","Papilloma","Dermoid cyst","Nevus"],a:1,e:"External hordeolum or stye is an acute staphylococcal infection involving glands of Zeis or eyelash follicles.<br><br>Pain, tenderness, and localized redness are characteristic findings.<br><br>Chalazion (A) is painless and chronic. Dermoid cyst (D) is congenital and noninflammatory.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is composed of melanocytes and may become darker during puberty?",o:["Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Nevus","Hemangioma","Chalazion"],a:2,e:"Eyelid nevus is a benign melanocytic lesion that may enlarge or darken during puberty because of hormonal influence.<br><br>Most lesions remain stable and benign throughout life.<br><br>Hemangioma (D) is vascular and reddish-blue rather than pigmented. Xanthelasma (B) appears yellow due to lipid deposition.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign vascular lesion commonly appears shortly after birth and enlarges rapidly during infancy?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Chalazion","Papilloma","Nevus","Capillary hemangioma"],a:4,e:"Capillary hemangioma is a benign vascular tumor of infancy that usually appears shortly after birth and proliferates rapidly during early childhood.<br><br>Large lesions may cause amblyopia by occluding the visual axis.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) grows slowly and is congenital. Papilloma (C) is epithelial rather than vascular.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion is classically painless and firm?",o:["Hordeolum","Furuncle","Cellulitis","Abscess","Chalazion"],a:4,e:"Chalazion presents as a painless firm eyelid swelling caused by chronic meibomian gland obstruction and granulomatous inflammation.<br><br>Hordeolum (A) is painful and acute because of bacterial infection. Cellulitis (C) produces diffuse inflammatory swelling.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is also known as \"stye\"?",o:["Chalazion","Xanthelasma","Papilloma","Nevus","Hordeolum externum"],a:4,e:"Stye refers to acute external hordeolum involving infection of eyelash follicles or associated sebaceous glands.<br><br>Pain and localized erythematous swelling are typical features.<br><br>Chalazion (A) is chronic and painless rather than acute and tender. Xanthelasma (B) is a lipid deposition lesion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid lesion may produce mechanical ptosis because of large size?",o:["Capillary hemangioma","Xanthelasma","Papilloma","Nevus","Chalazion"],a:0,e:"Large capillary hemangiomas may occlude the visual axis and produce mechanical ptosis, potentially causing deprivation amblyopia in infants.<br><br>Prompt treatment is required when vision is threatened.<br><br>Xanthelasma (B) is usually flat and cosmetic. Chalazion (E) rarely causes severe visual axis obstruction.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which lesion is best described as a congenital choristoma?",o:["Papilloma","Chalazion","Hordeolum","Xanthelasma","Dermoid cyst"],a:4,e:"Dermoid cyst is a congenital choristoma containing ectodermal tissue trapped along embryonic suture lines.<br><br>It commonly occurs at the frontozygomatic suture.<br><br>Papilloma (A) is an acquired epithelial proliferation. Hordeolum (C) is an acute infective process.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is commonly associated with chronic blepharitis and meibomian gland dysfunction?",o:["Chalazion","Nevus","Papilloma","Dermoid cyst","Hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Chronic blepharitis and meibomian gland dysfunction predispose to meibomian blockage and chalazion formation.<br><br>Recurrent chalazia are frequently associated with rosacea and lid inflammation.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (D) is congenital and unrelated to lid hygiene. Hemangioma (E) is vascular in origin.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion classically transilluminates poorly because of keratinous contents?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Capillary hemangioma","Papilloma","Nevus","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Dermoid cyst contains keratin, sebaceous material, and adnexal structures, resulting in poor transillumination.<br><br>It is usually smooth, painless, and slowly enlarging.<br><br>Capillary hemangioma (B) is vascular and may transilluminate better. Hordeolum (E) is inflammatory rather than cystic congenital lesion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which lesion consists histologically of lipid-laden foam cells?",o:["Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Nevus","Chalazion","Hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Xanthelasma contains collections of lipid-laden histiocytes or foam cells within the superficial dermis.<br><br>The lesions are soft, yellow, and frequently bilateral.<br><br>Nevus (C) contains melanocytes. Hemangioma (E) is composed of proliferating vascular channels.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion may regress spontaneously during childhood?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Chalazion","Nevus","Papilloma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:4,e:"Capillary hemangioma typically proliferates during infancy followed by spontaneous involution over several years.<br><br>Observation is appropriate unless amblyopia or cosmetic disfigurement develops.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) does not regress spontaneously. Papilloma (D) usually persists without involution.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is most commonly located near the medial canthus?",o:["Xanthelasma","Dermoid cyst","Hordeolum","Capillary hemangioma","Chalazion"],a:0,e:"Xanthelasma commonly develops near the medial canthus of upper and lower eyelids as yellow flat plaques.<br><br>The condition is cosmetically important and may indicate lipid abnormalities.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (B) usually occurs superotemporally near orbital sutures. Hordeolum (C) involves eyelash follicles or glands.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which lesion is most likely if a patient presents with acute painful red swelling at lid margin?",o:["Chalazion","Hordeolum externum","Dermoid cyst","Nevus","Papilloma"],a:1,e:"Acute painful erythematous swelling at the eyelid margin strongly suggests external hordeolum caused by staphylococcal infection.<br><br>Localized tenderness and pustule formation may occur. A recurrent or atypical chalazion warranting biopsy to exclude sebaceous carcinoma is a classic caution.<br><br>Chalazion (A) is painless and chronic. Papilloma (E) is noninflammatory and slowly growing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion may cause astigmatism if very large in children?",o:["Capillary hemangioma","Xanthelasma","Papilloma","Nevus","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Large capillary hemangiomas can exert pressure on the cornea causing induced astigmatism and amblyopia in young children.<br><br>Visual development monitoring is therefore essential.<br><br>Xanthelasma (B) and papilloma (C) are generally superficial lesions without significant corneal distortion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding chalazion is most accurate?",o:["It is always painful","It is a malignant tumor","It commonly arises from meibomian gland blockage","It is caused by retinal disease","It usually affects the optic nerve"],a:2,e:"Chalazion develops because of obstruction of a meibomian gland followed by chronic granulomatous inflammation.<br><br>It presents as a painless localized eyelid swelling.<br><br>Pain usually suggests acute hordeolum rather than chalazion. The lesion is benign and unrelated to retinal or optic nerve disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old man presents with recurrent unilateral \"chalazion\" of the upper lid for 8 months. Examination shows diffuse thickening of tarsal plate, loss of eyelashes, and yellowish discoloration of conjunctiva. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Capillary hemangioma","Hordeolum internum"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a highly malignant eyelid tumor that commonly masquerades as recurrent chalazion or chronic blepharoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Madarosis and diffuse tarsal thickening are important warning signs. Basal cell carcinoma as the commonest lid malignancy with its pearly rolled margin is a classic recognition theme.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) usually presents as pearly nodular ulcerative lesion rather than diffuse yellow tarsal infiltration. Hordeolum internum (E) is painful and acute.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe foreign body sensation, photophobia, and corneal epithelial defects due to inward rotation of the lower eyelid. Which factor is most important in involutional entropion pathogenesis?",o:["Orbital fat prolapse","Lower lid retractor disinsertion","Increased tear production","Facial nerve paralysis","Optic nerve dysfunction"],a:1,e:"Involutional entropion develops because of lower lid retractor weakness, horizontal lid laxity, and orbicularis override.<br><br>Retractor disinsertion is a major anatomical abnormality contributing to inward lid rotation. Involutional entropion with its mechanism in the elderly is a recurring lid-malposition question.<br><br>Facial nerve paralysis (D) commonly causes ectropion rather than entropion. Orbital fat prolapse (A) is unrelated to lid inversion mechanics.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe congenital ptosis keeps his chin elevated while walking and reading. Which complication is most important to prevent?",o:["Retinal detachment","Exposure keratopathy","Macular degeneration","Vitreous hemorrhage","Amblyopia"],a:4,e:"Congenital ptosis may obstruct the visual axis and interfere with normal visual development, leading to deprivation amblyopia.<br><br>Compensatory chin elevation is a classic clinical clue.<br><br>Exposure keratopathy (B) is more commonly associated with facial palsy or ectropion. Retinal detachment (A) is unrelated to congenital ptosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign eyelid lesion contains lipid-laden foam cells histologically and commonly occurs near the medial canthus?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Chalazion","Xanthelasma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:3,e:"Xanthelasma consists of superficial dermal collections of lipid-laden foam cells and commonly appears as yellow plaques near the medial canthus.<br><br>It may be associated with hyperlipidemia.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) is a congenital choristoma. Chalazion (C) is a lipogranulomatous inflammatory lesion of meibomian glands.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with complete ptosis, ophthalmoplegia, and dilated pupil. Which lesion must urgently be excluded?",o:["Pituitary microadenoma","Posterior communicating artery aneurysm","Retinitis pigmentosa","Orbital cellulitis","Keratoconus"],a:1,e:"Painful third nerve palsy with pupillary involvement strongly suggests compressive aneurysm involving the posterior communicating artery.<br><br>Urgent neuroimaging is essential because rupture may be fatal. Localising the cause of ptosis from the associated signs is a recurring neuro-ophthalmic exam theme.<br><br>Pituitary microadenoma (A) rarely causes acute complete third nerve palsy. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) affects retina rather than cranial nerves.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor is locally invasive with rare metastasis and classically affects the lower lid?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Merkel cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Basal cell carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the most common malignant eyelid tumor and is characterized by slow local invasion with extremely rare metastasis.<br><br>Lower eyelid and medial canthus are commonly affected.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) has greater metastatic potential and commonly involves the upper lid. Melanoma (D) is less common but highly metastatic.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding facial nerve palsy develops epiphora and exposure keratitis. Which eyelid abnormality is most likely responsible?",o:["Entropion","Cicatricial ptosis","Paralytic ectropion","Mechanical ptosis","Trichiasis"],a:2,e:"Facial nerve palsy weakens orbicularis oculi muscle, resulting in poor eyelid closure and outward turning of the lower lid.<br><br>Exposure keratopathy and watering are common consequences. Localising the cause of ptosis from the associated signs is a recurring neuro-ophthalmic exam theme.<br><br>Entropion (A) causes inward rotation with lash trauma rather than exposure-related dryness. Mechanical ptosis (D) causes drooping rather than lid eversion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which finding most strongly favors myasthenic ptosis over congenital ptosis?",o:["Absent lid crease","Chin elevation posture","Fatigability with sustained upgaze","Poor levator function","Lid lag on downgaze"],a:2,e:"Myasthenia gravis produces fluctuating fatigable ptosis that worsens after sustained muscle activity and improves with rest.<br><br>Fatigability is one of the most important differentiating clinical signs.<br><br>Poor levator function (D) and lid lag on downgaze (E) are more characteristic of congenital myogenic ptosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young child develops rapidly enlarging reddish-blue upper eyelid lesion causing visual axis obstruction. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Xanthelasma","Chalazion","Sebaceous cyst","Papilloma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:4,e:"Capillary hemangioma is a benign vascular tumor of infancy that may enlarge rapidly during early childhood.<br><br>Large lesions can induce amblyopia through visual axis obstruction or corneal astigmatism.<br><br>Chalazion (B) is a firm painless inflammatory lesion rather than a vascular bluish mass. Papilloma (D) is epithelial and pedunculated.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of entropion is most strongly associated with trachoma?",o:["Spastic entropion","Congenital entropion","Cicatricial entropion","Mechanical entropion","Senile entropion"],a:2,e:"Trachoma produces conjunctival fibrosis and posterior lamellar shortening, resulting in cicatricial entropion and trichiasis.<br><br>Corneal scarring from chronic lash trauma may cause blindness.<br><br>Senile entropion (E) develops because of age-related lid laxity rather than conjunctival scarring.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with severe unilateral ptosis that improves after application of an ice pack. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Horner syndrome","Congenital ptosis","Myasthenia gravis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Mechanical ptosis"],a:2,e:"Cooling improves neuromuscular transmission in myasthenia gravis, temporarily improving ptosis after ice pack application.<br><br>This bedside test is highly useful clinically. Localising the cause of ptosis from the associated signs is a recurring neuro-ophthalmic exam theme.<br><br>Horner syndrome (A) produces mild ptosis with miosis rather than fatigable fluctuating ptosis. Mechanical ptosis (E) results from heavy lid lesions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is best classified as a congenital choristoma?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Chalazion","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Dermoid cyst is a congenital choristoma containing ectodermal tissue trapped along embryonic suture lines.<br><br>It classically presents as painless superotemporal orbital swelling in children.<br><br>Papilloma (B) is an acquired epithelial proliferation. Hordeolum (E) is an acute infective lesion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid malignancy demonstrates pagetoid intraepithelial spread?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Papilloma","Nevus","Capillary hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is notorious for pagetoid spread within conjunctival and eyelid epithelium, contributing to delayed diagnosis.<br><br>This feature is heavily emphasized in postgraduate ophthalmology recalls.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) is locally invasive but typically lacks pagetoid epithelial spread. Papilloma (C) is benign.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which procedure is preferred in severe congenital ptosis with poor levator function?",o:["Trabeculectomy","Tarsorrhaphy only","Dacryocystorhinostomy","Lateral tarsal strip","Frontalis sling surgery"],a:4,e:"Frontalis sling surgery connects the eyelid to frontalis muscle, allowing brow elevation to elevate the eyelid in severe congenital ptosis.<br><br>It is especially useful when levator function is poor.<br><br>Lateral tarsal strip (D) corrects ectropion or entropion rather than ptosis. Trabeculectomy (A) is glaucoma filtration surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most characteristic of entropion?",o:["Painless yellow plaque","Night blindness","Pulsatile proptosis","Colored halos","Foreign body sensation"],a:4,e:"Entropion causes inward turning of eyelashes toward the cornea, producing persistent irritation and foreign body sensation.<br><br>Corneal abrasion and ulceration may occur if untreated.<br><br>Colored halos (D) suggest corneal edema in glaucoma. Pulsatile proptosis (C) occurs in carotid-cavernous fistula.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient has mild ptosis, miosis, and facial anhidrosis without ophthalmoplegia. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Horner syndrome","Orbital cellulitis","Marcus Gunn phenomenon"],a:2,e:"Horner syndrome results from interruption of sympathetic innervation and presents with mild ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis.<br><br>Ocular movements remain normal because cranial nerves controlling extraocular muscles are unaffected. Localising the cause of ptosis from the associated signs is a recurring neuro-ophthalmic exam theme.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) causes ophthalmoplegia and mydriasis rather than miosis. Myasthenia gravis (B) spares the pupil.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign lesion is most commonly associated with chronic blepharitis and meibomian dysfunction?",o:["Chalazion","Nevus","Dermoid cyst","Hemangioma","Papilloma"],a:0,e:"Chalazion commonly develops because chronic blepharitis and meibomian gland dysfunction obstruct glandular secretions.<br><br>Recurrent lesions are frequently seen in rosacea patients.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (C) is congenital. Hemangioma (D) is vascular and unrelated to lid margin inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with elderly-onset ptosis has high lid crease and good levator function. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Myogenic ptosis","Congenital ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Neurogenic ptosis","Mechanical ptosis"],a:2,e:"Aponeurotic ptosis results from levator aponeurosis stretching or dehiscence, commonly occurring in elderly patients.<br><br>High eyelid crease with preserved levator strength is characteristic.<br><br>Congenital ptosis (B) usually demonstrates poor levator function and absent lid crease. Mechanical ptosis (E) results from heavy masses.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which malignant eyelid tumor most commonly affects the upper eyelid because of abundant meibomian glands?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Squamous papilloma","Melanocytic nevus","Sebaceous gland carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma commonly arises from meibomian glands and therefore frequently affects the upper eyelid.<br><br>Its aggressive nature and masquerade presentation make early diagnosis essential.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) more commonly affects the lower lid. Nevus (D) is benign melanocytic proliferation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"An elderly patient presents with outward turning of the lower eyelid causing punctal eversion and chronic tearing. Which condition is most likely?",o:["Entropion","Paralytic ptosis","Involutional ectropion","Trichiasis","Blepharospasm"],a:2,e:"Involutional ectropion results from age-related horizontal lid laxity causing outward turning of the lower eyelid and punctal eversion.<br><br>Epiphora is a characteristic symptom because tear drainage becomes ineffective.<br><br>Entropion (A) causes inward rotation with lash irritation. Trichiasis (D) refers to misdirected eyelashes without lid eversion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 71-year-old woman is referred for a \"recurrent chalazion\" of the right upper lid. She has diffuse thickening of the tarsus, loss of eyelashes, and persistent unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis despite repeated incision and curettage. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Xanthelasma","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a classic masquerade tumor that often looks like recurrent chalazion or chronic unilateral blepharitis. Madarosis and diffuse tarsal thickening are important red flags.<br><br>It most often arises from meibomian glands in the upper lid and can spread pagetoidly over conjunctiva, which is why it is so often missed early.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) more often looks pearly with rolled borders, while xanthelasma (D) is soft and yellow rather than infiltrative.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 66-year-old man with long sun exposure develops a slowly enlarging lower lid lesion. Examination shows a pearly nodule with rolled edges and surface telangiectasia; there is no pain, but the lesion has begun to ulcerate centrally. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Chalazion","Papilloma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the commonest malignant eyelid tumor and classically presents as a pearly nodular lesion with rolled margins and telangiectasia. Public recall posts repeatedly flag this \"shiny lower lid nodule\" pattern.<br><br>It usually affects the lower lid and medial canthus and is locally destructive but rarely metastasizes. That is the key exam contrast with sebaceous carcinoma and melanoma.<br><br>Chalazion (C) is a painless meibomian blockage, and papilloma (D) is usually a benign fleshy/warty lesion rather than an ulcerated pearly nodule.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 78-year-old patient has worsening lower lid turning inward, foreign body sensation, tearing, and corneal staining. On examination, the lid is lax horizontally and the lower lid retractors appear weak on downgaze. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Cicatricial entropion","Involutional entropion","Paralytic ectropion","Mechanical ptosis","Congenital ectropion"],a:1,e:"Involutional entropion is the most common form of entropion in the elderly and is caused by age-related lid laxity with lower lid retractor weakness. Public and clinical recall sources repeatedly describe the lower lid turning inward in aging patients.<br><br>The lash-cornea touch explains the irritation, redness, and epithelial staining. ([[AAO<br><br>Cicatricial entropion (A) is due to scarring, while paralytic ectropion (C) follows facial nerve weakness and turns the lid outward.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 59-year-old woman with old facial nerve palsy complains of chronic watering and irritation. The lower lid is everted, the punctum is not apposed to the globe, and the exposed conjunctiva is dry and inflamed. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Involutional ectropion","Cicatricial ectropion","Paralytic ectropion","Entropion","Aponeurotic ptosis"],a:2,e:"Paralytic ectropion occurs when facial nerve palsy weakens orbicularis oculi, so the lower lid sags outward and punctal drainage fails. That gives the classic epiphora-plus-exposure picture seen in recall-style eyelid questions.<br><br>The key distinction is that the problem is muscle paralysis, not scarring or aging alone. Management often needs lid support and corneal protection.<br><br>Involutional ectropion (A) is age-related laxity, while cicatricial ectropion (B) is scar traction, often after burns.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient has mild upper lid drooping on one side, a constricted pupil, facial dryness on the same side, and no limitation of extraocular movements. Which lesion is most likely?",o:["Third nerve palsy","Horner syndrome","Myasthenia gravis","Congenital ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis"],a:1,e:"Horner syndrome causes mild ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis because the sympathetic supply to Muller muscle and the face is interrupted. Ptosis recall posts frequently list Horner among the main neurogenic causes.<br><br>The ptosis is usually subtle compared with third nerve palsy, and the pupil is small rather than dilated. Normal ocular motility is a major clue.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) usually gives ophthalmoplegia with mydriasis, and myasthenia gravis (C) tends to fluctuate rather than produce miosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 34-year-old woman reports that her eyelid droop worsens by evening and improves after rest. She also has intermittent diplopia. The ice pack test temporarily improves her ptosis. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Horner syndrome","Myasthenia gravis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Congenital ptosis","Mechanical ptosis"],a:1,e:"Fluctuating ptosis that worsens with fatigue and improves with rest is classic for myasthenia gravis, and public recall posts repeatedly emphasize this pattern. The ice-pack response is a high-yield bedside clue.<br><br>Pupils are usually normal, which helps distinguish it from Horner syndrome or compressive third nerve palsy. Diplopia is common because extraocular muscles fatigue too.<br><br>Aponeurotic ptosis (C) is usually stable with age and high lid crease, not fluctuating through the day.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"An elderly patient has unilateral ptosis after cataract surgery. The levator function is good, the eyelid crease is high, and there is no pupil abnormality or diplopia. Which type of ptosis is most likely?",o:["Myogenic ptosis","Mechanical ptosis","Horner syndrome","Congenital ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis"],a:4,e:"Aponeurotic ptosis is the common age-related or postoperative ptosis caused by levator aponeurosis stretching or dehiscence. Public notes specifically mention levator stretching as the mechanism.<br><br>A high lid crease and preserved levator function are classic clues. The pupil and eye movements remain normal.<br><br>Myogenic ptosis (A) usually has poor levator function, while Horner syndrome (C) would give miosis and a milder droop.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child has unilateral ptosis since birth. The parent reports that the child constantly lifts the chin to see the board, and the drooping lid partially covers the pupil. Which complication must be actively prevented?",o:["Papilledema","Corneal graft rejection","Retinal detachment","Ptosis progression to Horner syndrome","Amblyopia"],a:4,e:"Congenital ptosis is a classic pediatric cause of deprivation amblyopia if the visual axis is covered, and public ptosis notes explicitly warn that ptosis can affect vision in children.<br><br>The chin-up posture is a typical compensatory sign. When levator function is poor or the pupil is occluded, early surgery may be needed to protect vision.<br><br>Papilledema (A) is an intracranial disc swelling problem, not a congenital lid droop complication.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A mother brings a newborn whose upper lid rises whenever the baby sucks or moves the jaw. The eyelid droop is present since birth and is usually unilateral. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Marcus Gunn jaw-winking syndrome","Horner syndrome","Aponeurotic ptosis","Myasthenia gravis","Mechanical ptosis"],a:0,e:"Marcus Gunn jaw-winking syndrome is a congenital synkinesis in which jaw movement triggers upper lid elevation. Public recall posts describe it as eyelid movement during chewing or sucking.<br><br>It is a classic congenital ptosis variant and can be cosmetically obvious in infancy. The lid movement with mastication is the exam giveaway.<br><br>Horner syndrome (B) gives miosis and mild ptosis, but not jaw-triggered lid elevation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 7-month-old infant has a bright red, compressible eyelid mass that enlarged rapidly after birth. The lesion is obstructing the visual axis, and the child is developing amblyopia risk and astigmatism. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Chalazion","Papilloma","Xanthelasma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:4,e:"Capillary hemangioma is the classic benign vascular tumor of infancy and can produce amblyopia by occluding the visual axis or causing induced astigmatism. Public recall notes repeatedly emphasize the \"strawberry\" lesion and vision risk.<br><br>It often proliferates early and may later involute, but intervention is needed when vision is threatened. This is why it is a favorite high-yield pediatric eyelid question.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) is congenital and slow-growing near sutures, not a rapidly proliferating vascular mass.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old woman notices soft yellow plaques near the inner canthus of both upper eyelids. They are flat, painless, and cosmetically bothersome. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Xanthelasma","Chalazion","Papilloma","Dermoid cyst","Hordeolum"],a:0,e:"Xanthelasma presents as soft yellow cholesterol-rich plaques near the medial canthus, often bilaterally and more often on the upper lid. Public notes consistently describe these as harmless yellow eyelid deposits.<br><br>It may be associated with hyperlipidemia, diabetes, or thyroid disease, but can also occur with normal lipids. The main clinical importance is recognizing the systemic clue. ([[Cleveland<br><br>Chalazion (B) is a meibomian blockage nodule, usually firmer and not characteristically yellow plaques.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 29-year-old woman has a slowly enlarging painless upper lid lump that has been present since childhood. It is located near the superotemporal orbital rim, and imaging suggests a congenital cystic lesion. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Papilloma","Chalazion","Xanthelasma","Sebaceous carcinoma"],a:0,e:"Dermoid cysts are congenital choristomas that commonly occur near the frontozygomatic suture and present as painless, slowly enlarging superotemporal masses. Public notes and surgical posts repeatedly place them in children near the brow/orbital rim.<br><br>They are typically benign and may be noticed early in life. The location and long history are the key clues, making this a very classic eyelid recall.<br><br>Papilloma (B) is usually a fleshy epithelial growth, not a congenital suture-line cyst.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with a small, flesh-colored, pedunculated eyelid lesion that looks like a skin tag. It is painless and has slowly grown over months. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Papilloma","Sebaceous carcinoma","Chalazion","Hordeolum","Capillary hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Eyelid papilloma is a common benign lesion and is often described as a small fleshy or skin-tag-like growth. Public recall notes associate papilloma with benign eyelid warts and HPV-related growths.<br><br>It is typically slow-growing and noninvasive. That makes it a useful contrast with sebaceous carcinoma, which may masquerade as inflammation or chalazion rather than a simple tag.<br><br>Chalazion (C) is a deep painless meibomian nodule, not a pedunculated epithelial lesion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 23-year-old man develops a painless firm nodule in the upper lid. There is mild tenderness only if squeezed, and the lesion slowly enlarges over weeks. Examination suggests a blocked meibomian gland rather than infection. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Hordeolum externum","Chalazion","Papilloma","Basal cell carcinoma","Xanthelasma"],a:1,e:"Chalazion is a common benign inflammatory nodule caused by blockage of a meibomian gland, and multiple public recall notes call it a painless eyelid lump.<br><br>It is more chronic and less tender than hordeolum. Recurrent or atypical lesions in older adults should raise concern for sebaceous carcinoma.<br><br>Hordeolum externum (A) is the acute painful stye, whereas xanthelasma (E) is a soft yellow plaque near the canthus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old smoker develops a rapidly enlarging, scaly, ulcerative lesion on the lower eyelid that looks keratinized and has irregular borders. There is local lid margin destruction but no greasy yellow tarsal thickening. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Squamous cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Papilloma","Chalazion","Dermoid cyst"],a:0,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma is a malignant eyelid tumor that tends to look ulcerative, scaly, and keratinizing, with more local aggressiveness than basal cell carcinoma. Public eyelid tumor notes list it among the common malignant eyelid tumors.<br><br>Compared with sebaceous carcinoma, it is less likely to mimic chalazion and more likely to show a keratinizing surface. Lymphatic spread is more relevant than in basal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Papilloma (C) remains benign and pedunculated, while chalazion (D) is inflammatory and typically painless.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 6-month-old baby has a large upper eyelid vascular mass that intermittently droops the lid over the pupil. The lesion is soft, compressible, and bright red. Which term best describes the resulting lid position problem?",o:["Mechanical ptosis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Myasthenic ptosis","Horner ptosis","Congenital ectropion"],a:0,e:"A bulky eyelid mass can mechanically weigh down the upper lid and produce ptosis. Capillary hemangioma is a classic infant cause, and public recall posts note that periocular hemangiomas can cause amblyopia and lid obstruction.<br><br>This differs from aponeurotic ptosis, which is due to levator aponeurosis stretching in older adults. The key exam clue is the heavy lesion rather than nerve or muscle disease.<br><br>Myasthenic ptosis (C) fluctuates, and Horner ptosis (D) is mild with miosis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 74-year-old man with a history of sun exposure has an eyelid lesion that is pearly, rolled, and slowly ulcerating. The lesion has been present for years and has started to distort the medial canthus. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Xanthelasma","Papilloma","Chalazion"],a:0,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the most common malignant eyelid tumor and classically presents as a pearly lesion with rolled edges and telangiectasia. Public recall-style notes repeatedly list it as the commonest eyelid malignancy.<br><br>The lower lid and medial canthus are favored sites because of chronic ultraviolet exposure, and the tumor is locally destructive rather than widely metastatic. That is why exam questions often describe slow ulceration and lid-margin loss.<br><br>Xanthelasma (C) is soft yellow plaque, while chalazion (E) is a painless meibomian nodule, not a rolled ulcer.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 69-year-old woman has bilateral lower lid turning inward. She reports frequent corneal irritation, tearing, and worse symptoms when she squeezes her eyes shut. Examination reveals horizontal lid laxity and lower lid retractor weakness. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Spastic entropion","Congenital ptosis","Cicatricial ectropion","Paralytic ectropion","Involutional entropion"],a:4,e:"Involutional entropion is the most common entropion in older adults and is caused by age-related horizontal laxity plus lower lid retractor weakness. Public and specialty notes repeatedly emphasize this mechanism.<br><br>The squeezing maneuver can bring out the inward rotation because orbicularis override pushes the lid margin toward the globe. That is why the cornea gets rubbed and stained. ([[Ento<br><br>Cicatricial ectropion (C) is scar-driven outward eversion, and paralytic ectropion (D) is facial-nerve related outward turning.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 61-year-old woman with long-standing burns around the lower face has an outward-turned lower eyelid and severe tearing. The punctum is everted and the ocular surface is exposed. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Involutional ectropion","Horner syndrome","Mechanical ptosis","Entropion","Cicatricial ectropion"],a:4,e:"Cicatricial ectropion is caused by scarring and contracture of the anterior lamella, classically after burns, trauma, or chronic dermatitis. Public eyelid posts describe ectropion as an outward-turning lower lid that exposes the inner surface.<br><br>The punctum turns away from the tear meniscus, so epiphora and exposure keratopathy are expected. This is the key contrast with involutional ectropion, where age-related laxity dominates.<br><br>Entropion (D) turns the lid inward and causes lash trauma rather than punctal eversion. ([[Cleveland<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old man presents with severe unilateral ptosis, a dilated pupil, and the eye positioned \"down and out.\" He also has a painful headache. Which diagnosis is most urgent to exclude?",o:["Horner syndrome","Posterior communicating artery aneurysm causing third nerve palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Aponeurotic ptosis","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Painful third nerve palsy with mydriasis is a classic emergency because a compressive posterior communicating artery aneurysm must be excluded urgently. Ptosis posts repeatedly list nerve damage and third nerve involvement as major causes of drooping eyelid.<br><br>The pupil is affected because parasympathetic fibers run superficially on the nerve and are vulnerable to compression. The \"down and out\" position reflects unopposed lateral rectus and superior oblique action.<br><br>Horner syndrome (A) gives a small pupil, and myasthenia gravis (C) usually spares the pupil and fluctuates.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
];